        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1683820536" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6598462153903668239"><i>A Moment&apos;s Halt--a momentary taste <br/>Of Being from the Well amid the Waste-- <br/>And Lo!--the phantom Caravan has reach&apos;d <br/>The Nothing it set out from--Oh, make haste!</i><br/>——from the Rubaiyat of Omar Khayam<br/><br/>In the late 1960s at the age of 51, Dr. Alice Bradley Sheldon, a scientist and artist who had served in the U.S. Army and Central Intelligence Agency, began, covertly, to write. Under the masculine persona of James Tiptree Jr., and occasionally as the masked-woman Raccoona Sheldon, she published a body of</span>
  <span id="freeText6598462153903668239" style="display:none"><i>A Moment's Halt--a momentary taste <br />Of Being from the Well amid the Waste-- <br />And Lo!--the phantom Caravan has reach'd <br />The Nothing it set out from--Oh, make haste!</i><br />——from the Rubaiyat of Omar Khayam<br /><br />In the late 1960s at the age of 51, Dr. Alice Bradley Sheldon, a scientist and artist who had served in the U.S. Army and Central Intelligence Agency, began, covertly, to write. Under the masculine persona of James Tiptree Jr., and occasionally as the masked-woman Raccoona Sheldon, she published a body of disturbing, complex, and often entrancing science fiction short stories dealing with gender and violence, social exclusion, isolation and the longing for intimacy, and the biological drives that can push a species to survive — or to its doom. While she wrote under a man’s name, most of her protagonists were women and her stories were distinctly feminist. Some are very strong, original and memorable. She has influenced many prominent writers of speculative fiction. Her prose has power and beauty, and to my surprise and delight, almost every story integrates quotations from well-known poets — Khayyam, Blake, Yeats, Keats, Swinburne, Tennyson, Longfellow, and many others. <br /><br /><i>Move upward, working out the beast, <br />And let the ape and tiger die.</i><br />— — Alfred Lord Tennyson, In Memoriam A. H. H. OBIIT MDCCCXXXIII: 118<br /><br />If you envision the triumph of rationality for humankind, Dr. Sheldon would beg to differ. Nineteenth-century optimism may have imagined the demise of Man’s inner ape and tiger, but Tiptree/Sheldon wrote in the aftermath of twentieth century wars that exceeded human imagination in creative brutality. Biological imperatives loom large in these stories, drives that use the human mind — sometimes the entire human race — as their plaything. <br /><br /><i>We pieced our thoughts into philosophy,<br />And planned to bring the world under a rule,<br />Who are but weasels fighting in a hole.</i><br />— — W. B. Yeats, Nineteen Hundred and Nineteen<br /><br />There’s a lot of reference to sex in these stories — but very little of it involves lovemaking or intimacy. It’s for procreation, to fulfill a drive — and sometimes, to inflict humiliation. There’s a lot of sexual violence. (One can only imagine what Sheldon might have seen, heard or experienced in her time in the Army and CIA.) But while Sheldon’s overall sensibility is tragic and even fatalistic, her stories also express authentic love, intimacy, friendship, caring. sacrifice, and even, rarely, mutual erotic love. <br /><br /><i>What is it men in women do require? <br />The lineaments of Gratified Desire. <br />What is it women do in men require? <br />The lineaments of Gratified Desire.</i><br />— — Willam Blake<br /><br />Often Tiptree’s characters are isolated individuals from the bottom of the socio-economic pecking order, who are frustrated in their quests for the goods of life -- including their quest for love. But when people (or creatures) do find love, they tend to die -- or even kill each other -- shortly thereafter. There’s no exploration of the dynamics of long-term relationships — something I especially appreciate in literature. Sheldon has been criticized for almost always “solving” the literary ending problem with death, and it may be a valid criticism. But the end of life is often handled imaginatively and ambiguously — some involving self-sacrifice for others; some implying continuation in some other natural but not necessarily corporeal form, though these other forms range from ecstatic to hellish. A very few of the stories revealed a romantic streak hidden under her hard edge pessimism, and I have to admit I liked that. <br /><br />The book includes 18 stories for a total of 500+ pages; I appreciated all of them. Here are a few thoughts on a few favorites. Stop here if you don’t want any spoilers at all.<br /><br />In <b>The Screwfly Solution</b> (1977) a happily married man and woman must do everything in their power not to see each other again. The man has succumbed to a mysterious plague that has intensified the violent aspects of men’s sexuality. This story explores our nature as biological organisms whose minds, emotions, and even beliefs may be subject to manipulation and chemically-induced psychosis. In this and many other stories, Tiptree explores connections between sex and violence, and the possibility of choosing to act in opposition to biological drives when those drives are harmful to others. <br /><br /><b>“The Girl Who Was Plugged In”</b> (1973) confronts all-pervasive consumer culture, as well as the merging of human and machine. While some of the other tales in this collection feel a bit dated, this one seems even more relevant today than when it was first published. This story and my favorite, the infinitely weird <b>“With Delicate Mad Hands,”</b> (1981) both involve young woman protagonists who are intelligent and talented but exceptionally unattractive because of a physical deformity and because her financial circumstances make it impossible for her to have the surgery/cosmetic treatments that would render her “normal” looking and attractive. (Imagine if you had a daughter who was born with a pig’s snout instead of a human nose.) In these stories, Tiptree/Sheldon uses the kind of harsh, derogatory language that some men use among themselves when discussing the physical appearance of a woman they think is ugly. This was jarring, uncomfortable, and very powerful. The Girl in the first story, who has attempted suicide, is “rescued” by a commercial enterprise wanting to use her as the remote operator of a gorgeous young avatar for advertising purposes. She proves exceptionally good at imbuing her avatar with personality -- but too honest about the products she is supposed to be promoting -- drawing the attention of an independent-minded young man, who falls in love with her -- in the form of her avatar. Beyond the sci-fi aspects there’s a real exploration of social isolation. <br /><br /><b>With Delicate Mad Hands</b> is an astonishing story of a young woman determined to be the first woman to pilot spaceships, and subject to all kinds of brutality along the way. This almost surreal story moves through all kinds of twists and turns -- every time you think “this is it” it heads off in another direction. There’s even a tribute to Yoda. This is a rare story where two misfit soulmates find each other and love each other, in a boundary-crossing, but nonsexual, love relationship, with a conclusion both joyful and tragic. <br /><br /><b>Your Faces, O My Sisters! Your Faces Filled of Light!</b> (1976) enchanted me -- even against my better judgment -- maybe because I love to take long walks and have done so through many cities, even in dangerous neighborhoods at night -- sometimes this was out of necessity, when I was returning from work or school at night, for example -- always with an element of fear and often with unwanted attention and occasional harassment or even assault. So when the young woman in this story walks at night through a dangerous big city — Chicago, maybe — radiantly happy in her job as a walking courier, walking without without fear, in confidence, in a world without men -- I loved it. (I’m happily married to a man, but don’t like walking through cities because of the way some men act.) This happy young woman chants as she walks, lines from Longfellow’s sing-song epic Hiawatha -- which would be great to chant on her walk of several hundred miles. Even though we quickly learn that things are not as good as they seem, I found the spell of her delusional world lastingly powerful because of the sense of power and freedom she had achieved in life despite, or rather, because of, her mental illness. <br /><br /><b>Love is the Plan the Plan is Death</b> (1973) is uniquely lyrical and erotic love story — between two spiderlike aliens. A gem of a weird story. <br /><br /><b>A Momentary Taste of Being</b> (1975) was the only story that seemed too long and too slow — but ultimately fascinating conceptually, so worth reading to the ambiguous end -- ecstatically joyful or tragic? Yes and yes. <br /><br /><b>We Who Stole the Dream</b> (1978) dealt with the liberation of a people and the ethical challenges that face them in finding that some of their own people have adopted the ways of their oppressors. <br /><br /><b>Slow Music</b> (1980) is about a woman who wants to remain on Earth and “do human things” when most if not all humans are opting for a path that will transform them into non corporeal beings. -- something that seems closer to potential reality today.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6598462153903668239" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


